Data Analysis Project¶

Data set analyzed: tmdb-movies.csv¶

Questions posed:¶

Since I am analyzing a movie data set, I will be trying to examine this as an entertainment service, such as Netflix or Amazon Video, would. Thus, I want to investigate which factors influence which movies will be the most popular and most highly viewed. This will help me to generate the most revenue and give my viewers the best experience possible.
So my fundamental question is this: Which factors most strongly influence the popularity of a movie?

We can derive some further questions from this most fundamental one: Are more recently released movies more popular?
Do higher budget films tend to be more popular?
Does runtime affect the popularity of a movie?
Do the genres of a movie affect its popularity?
Do genres from certain time periods have a higher popularity rating than other genres of the same time period?
Do all years have the same or similar amounts of movies stored in this database?

These are just some guide questions and I will not be answering them all necesairly.

Terms:¶

I would like to label some terms, both for my future self and for anyone else who will be examing this document.

gbo = dataframe group by object. Used as a suffix extension (data_gbo)¶

dict = dictionary. Used as suffix extension (data_dict)¶

Important Note:¶

As I have gone through the process of analyzing this data, I have learned how to do it more efficiently. You will see this progression. This progression is mainly in the functions I wrote to wrangle and display data more effectively. For the blocks of code before I wrote and implemented these functions I chose not to go back and revise the code for the purpose of seeing this progression. Often I thought at first that it would just be easier to skip writing a function and do all the leg work myself. However, as my analysis grew increasingly complex, I realized it would be much easier just to have a function do the work.

Also, you'll notice inconsistencies in my code (such as how I named lists and dataframes e.g. swtiching from '' to "" in my lists. Again, I could have gone back and made the code completely consistent but I chose not to because I wanted the my progression and code development to be evident.

def find_rows(movie_list):
    """Finds rows for each movie in movie_rows. Meant to be used with create_dataframe().
    Returns a list of row numbers."""
    rows = []
    for movie in movie_list:   
        row_num = int(movies_df.loc[movies_df['original_title'] == movie].index[0])
        rows.append(row_num)
    return rows
In [223]:
def find_mean_year_popularity(year_list):
    """Finds the mean popularities for years in a list. Returns a list of means.
    Meant to be used with create_dataframe()."""
    popularity_list = []
    for year in year_list:
        popularity = movies_df.groupby('release_year')\
                ['popularity'].get_group(year).mean()
        popularity_list.append(popularity)
    return np.asarray(popularity_list)

def create_dataframe(movie_list):
    """Takes a list of movies and returns a pandas DataFrame of the following form:
    DataFrame = ({
    'title':['one', 'two', 'three'...]
    'release_year':['2000', '2001', '2002'...]
    'popularity':[1,2,3...]
    'mean_year_popularity':[1,2,3]
    })
    Movies in list must be strings and valid movie titles in the movies_df dataframe. 
    Ideally this function will be used for movies in one series, but it could be used
    for any movies. And really, any column could be added to this function. 
    """
    new_df = pd.DataFrame({
        'title':[],
        'release_year':[],
        'popularity':[],
        'mean_year_popularity':[],
        'vote_count':[],
        'vote_average':[]
    })
    rows = find_rows(movie_list)
    new_df['title'] = movies_df.iloc[rows]['original_title']
    new_df['release_year'] = movies_df.iloc[rows]['release_year']
    release_years = list(movies_df.iloc[rows]['release_year'])
    new_df['popularity'] = movies_df.iloc[rows]['popularity']
    year_popularities = find_mean_year_popularity(release_years)
    new_df['mean_year_popularity'] = year_popularities
    new_df['vote_count'] = movies_df.iloc[rows]['vote_count']
    new_df['vote_average'] = movies_df.iloc[rows]['vote_average']
    return new_df

def find_movies_by_title(title):
    """Returns any movie in which the title argument is at least partially present.
    Be careful if looking for movies in a series because sometimes the main title
    is not at all present in the title for some movies."""
    return movies_df[movies_df['original_title'].str.contains(title)]
In [226]:
def find_movies_by_search(column, value):
    """Retruns any movie for which the value in the column is equal to the
    value searched for. The two arguments must be exactly equal."""
    return movies_df[movies_df[column] == value]

def create_pop_plot(dataframe, series_title):
    """Creates a bar graph for a given data set comparing the popularity and
    mean_year_popularity for each movie in the data set."""
    new_plot = dataframe.plot(dataframe['title'],['popularity','mean_year_popularity']
                                 , kind='bar')
    new_plot.set_xlabel('Movie Title')
    new_plot.set_ylabel('Popularity')
    new_plot.set_title('Popularity and average year popularity for {} films'.format(series_title))
    return new_plot

def popularity_score(dataframe):
    """Takes a dataframe of a series of movies as input and outputs a score of the mean 
    of how popular each movie is compared to the mean popularity for each movie's year.
    The higher the score the higher in general each movie's popularity is compared to its 
    year's mean popularity. If a score is negative then that means the average popularities
    of the movies in the series are lower than the average popularities for their
    respective years."""
    popularity_mean = dataframe['popularity'].mean()
    mean_year_popularity_mean = dataframe['mean_year_popularity'].mean()
    return popularity_mean - mean_year_popularity_mean
In [229]:
def corr_coef(series_dataframe):
    """Takes as input a series dataframe and returns the correlation coefficient between
    the popularities and mean_year_popularities for each movie."""
    return series_dataframe['popularity'].corr(series_dataframe['mean_year_popularity'])

def standardize_data(dataframe):
    """Standardizes data to allow data of different metrics to be compared."""
    return (dataframe - (dataframe.mean()))/dataframe.std()

Looking at this information, we see that the movie with the highest popularity per year increases fairly regularly over time. However, when we get to 2014 and 2015, the numbers suddenly sky rocket. This data was collected in 2015, which means that the most popular movies at a given time tend to be those produced within a year or two. Looking at this data, you can also gain a sense for which years were not great for film.

So for the most part, the data is relatively steady -other than the most recent two years. There is one year I'd like to examine because it's most popular movie is extraordinairly high. That year is 1977. Now, my guess is that the movie causing this spike is Star Wars IV (the first one ever made). Lets take a look.

Ah, just as I predicted. It makes sense, really, that this is the movie causing the spike; this is one of the most iconic movies of all time, plus its sequel Star Wars: The Force Awakens came out in 2015. Since this data was collected in 2015, I'd say more people than average were watching Star Wars in preparation for it's sequel. And now I'm curious. I want to see how the other Star Wars movies compare. If they're all at the top of their popularities for their respective years or not. More on this later.

Getting back to the fundamental question, which factors most strongly influence the popularity of a movie, we already have a solid answer. Time, more specifically the year released, has a very strong influence on which movies will be most popular.

Star Wars films¶

So as I found before, the original Star Wars film was far more popular than any other film for the span of a few decades. I attribute this to the fact that Star Wars is one of the most iconic films ever made and that a new Star Wars movie had come out in the same year this data was collected. Now I also want to see how the other Star Wars films stack up for their years. I'll start by examining how popular each film is and see where the trail leads.

So, it's interesting to see that the average popularity for each year is about the same, and each Star Wars movie is still high above it, even if not quite as high the original film. This indicates to me that perhaps people started to watch the original Star Wars but didn't want to watch the entire series. Each film becomes progressively less popuar, with the exception of Revenge of the Sith. So perhaps people got excited about watching the first one, and many were satisfied with just watching that. All the movies after the first one decrease in popularity (generally), but not as sharply as popularity decreased from the first film to the second one. So, my conclusion is that if you decide to watch the second movie in the series then there is a high chance that you'll watch more if not all of them.

Star Wars is unique in that there have been many movies made in the series. There are very few other movie series like that to my knowledge. My tentative conclusion at this point is that when there is a new movie coming out that is part of a series, popularity for the other movies in that series increases as well, but not as much as it did for the Star Wars films. I say this because the Star Wars films span several decades, and so the original films fall into the category of "popular when our parents were young" (I'm 20, by the way). This means that there are now many people who haven't seen any Star Wars movies. So people, in preparation for the new Star Wars movie that was going to come out at the time this data was collected, wanted to have some backgroud knowledge of Star Wars before watching this new movie. Many watched the first one, didn't care enough to watch any others, and called it good. Most other movie series won't be like that because they don't span such a time frame as Star Wars. Many who will want to see a new movie coming out that is part of a series will have already seen the other movies in the series, and they wont be as inclined to go rewatch them. This, however, is only a hypothesis and not a conclusion. I cannot make a conclusion as I only have 2015 data to examine, and because of that I don't know how popular Star Wars movies are in years when a Star Wars movie is not coming out.

Okay! So even just looking through the first few movies released in 2015 I see that many are part of a series -far more than I expected. Because of this sheer volume, I'll only examine the first 5 movies that are part of large movie series, containing 3 or more movies (and I've already examined Star Wars). I will exclude Insurgent because it is only part of a two-movie series (at the time this data was collected). Also, its prequel Divergent was released in 2014 and was a very popular movie just on its own. I'm looking for older movies that may have regained popularity recently because of a new release in its series. Thus, I don't think this series would represent very well the common behavior of movie series in general.

Jurassic World (Jurassic Park series)¶

The chronological titles of all films in this series (when this data was collected) are: Jurassic Park, The Lost World: Jurassic Park, Jurassic Park III, and Jurassic World. Let's see how these movies compare in their respective years.

Movie Rankings¶

Now that we have examined all the different movie series and their data, lets see which series have been the most successful -or are at least the most popular. To do this I will be using my popularity_score function on each of the dataframes.

I'll explain how these scores work so they are more meaningful. The score is calculated by taking the mean of the popularities for the movies in a series and subtracting the mean for the mean year popularities for each movie from it. For example, say there are three movies in a series and their popularities are: 2,4,6. The mean year popularities are 1,2,3. The mean for the movie popularities = (2+4+6)/3 = 4. The mean for the mean year popularities = (1+2+3)/3 = 2. Subtract 2 from 4 and you are left with 2, so 2 is your score. The higher score, the better.

Looking at the popularity scores of each of these movie series, they all (except for one) are positive. Well... my hypothesis isn't looking too good right now. The popularity scores from these film series totally blows the ones examined in 2015 out of the water. I honestly thought that the Star Wars film series was vastly superior to all other film series... but Lord of the Rings is way more popular than Star Wars, plus the Iron Man film series strongly contends with the Star Wars series. I still think it's remarkable how the original Star Wars is so incredibly popular, especially considering its time period, but the series as a whole is not as unparalleled as I thought.

In fact, looking at the graphs for each 2013 series, there is not a single film that is less popular than the mean popularity for its year. Not a single one. That is surprising to say the least. The mean popularity score for 2015 series is 1.816862 while for 2013 series it is 3.074314. That means that the avarage popularity score for 2013 is almost double what it is in 2015. I think the only thing to do at this point is examine more data because right not it is terrible inconclusive. Now I will go back another two years and look at movies that came out in 2011 which are part of a series. I'll go back two years and not one to be able to move through data more quickly. I may have to look at several more years before a clear pattern forms and looking two years apart will, I believe, give a good samping of the data.

The mean popularity score for 2011 is almost twice that of 2015, and the 2011 minimum is well away from the negative (2015's is negative). The best thing going for 2015 is still that Star Wars has a very high popularity score still. So it appears that movie series trend opposite of what I predicted: They tend to become more popular after more time has passed. I'll now investigate 2009 movie series.

How does vote count correlate to year released?¶

There is an aspect of this data, vote_count, which I believe is how many people have voted any rating for a particular movie. My hypothesis is that the more recently a movie has been released, the higher vote_count value there will be for the movie. To examine this, I'll calculate the mean vote_count for each year and then compare that to the year released.

So the correlation between these two is almost 0, which means that there is a very weak correlation between the two aspects of the data. The vote average has almost no effect on the popularity of a movie, but the vote count has a very strong impact on the popularity. This means that for a movie to be popular, many people need to be paying attention to it, regardless of how good it actually is.

Conclusion¶

So, to answer the question Do movies in a movie series become more popular when a movie in that series has been released recently?, the answer is: maybe. There is far more work that would need to be done to come to a more rigorous conclusion about this data, work such as:

  • Examining data from several different years of collected data.

  • Examining data for all years within the collected sets of data.

    • To anwser the fundamental question Which factors most strongly influence the popularity of a movie?, it's clear that the year the movie was releasd is a strong factor in its popularity. The movies released within the last two years of this data being collected have higher mean and max popularities than the rest of the years, with max being the biggest difference. However, this conclusion is only tenative. Far more extensive analysis would have to be done to arrive at a more rigorous conclusion.

    The vote count of a movie seems to strongly influence its poularity as well. There was a very strong correlation between the mean vote count and mean popularities for the movies by year. The rating of the movies, however, seem not to be a strong influencer of popularity. The mean popularities of the movies rose (roughly) as time progressed, and, in fact, the average rating of the movies decreased. So the people who compile this data set are far more concerned with how many people are even paying attention to the movie and voting something for it, regardless of how good it actually is. However, this analysis is tenative and I cannot make any firm conclusions yet, so all my conclusions are tenative. Not enough analysis has been done to come to a firm conclusion.

    Limitations¶

    Even if I examined this data set as thoroughly as possible, it is only for one year. To properly answer the question of whether movies in a series become more popular when a new movie in that series is released, it would be necessary to follow the popularity of several, if not all, series over the years as new movies in them are released. This would be impossible for some movies, however, such as movies that were released before this database became collected. There would be no way to know their popularities because this metric (as far as I know) did not exist at the time. Even if I collected data for every series over every year within this 2015 database, I could only partially answer the question. Also, it was a bit difficult to find information on what some of the different aspects of the movies mean. For example, the highest movie popularity was about 33. I was unable to find how high it could possibly be or what the score really meant. So I assumed that the popularity is a combination of several other factors and used to make a movie more likely to be suggested than another. Because I don't fully know what these aspects mean, I could be misinterpreting some of them and drawing a false conclusion because of that.
